<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec_calc1" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Non-Constant Motion</title>
		
  <corollary xml:id="int-ncv">
	<title>Non-constant Velocity</title>
	
	<statement>
		<p>
			
		</p>

		<video youtube="26vbUjdFpBk"></video>
<!--<description>Using integrals in physics.</description>-->
	</statement>
  </corollary>
		  
      
    
	<subsubsection><title>Non-constant Velocity</title></subsubsection>

	  <p>
		Suppose you want to find the change in position for a situation where the velocity is a known, non-constant function <m>\vec{v}(t)</m>
	  </p>
	
	<p><term>Chop:</term> Start by chopping up a time interval into small pieces.  Each piece of time is represented by the expression <m>dt</m>, where the <m>d</m> indicates that the amount of time is <em>infinitesimally small</em>.</p>
	
	<p><term>Multiply:</term> You want to know about position, but you know about velocity.  Although you want <m>\Delta \vec{r}</m>, the change in position over a whole time interval, you can start by trying to find an infinitesimal change in position <m>d\vec{r}</m>.  By rewriting the definition of instantaneous velocity as <m>d \vec{r} = \vec{v}(t) dt</m>, you can see that a way to get <m>d\vec{r}</m> is to <em>multiply</em> <m>\vec{v}(t)</m> and <m>dt</m>.</p>
	
		<p><term>Add:</term> Last, once you have the infinitesimal <m>d\vec{r}</m>, you need to <em>add</em> together every <m>d\vec{r}</m> over the full times of interest, which can be done with an integral: <me>\int_{r_i}^{r_f}d \vec{r} = \int_{t_i}^{t_f} \vec{v}(t) dt</me>  The left hand side of this equation can be easily evaluated to give <me>\Delta \vec{r} = \int_{t_i}^{t_f} \vec{v}(t) dt</me></p>

	  <subsubsection><title>Non-constant Acceleration</title></subsubsection>

	  <p>
		Suppose you want to find the change in velocity for a situation where the acceleration is a known, non-constant function <m>\vec{a}(t)</m>
	  </p>
	
	<p><term>Chop:</term> Start by chopping up a time interval into small pieces.  Each piece of time is represented by the expression <m>dt</m>, where the <m>d</m> indicates that the amount of time is <em>infinitesimally small</em>.</p>
	
	<p><term>Multiply:</term> You want to know about velocity, but you know about acceleration.  Although you want <m>\Delta \vec{v}</m>, the change in velocity over a whole time interval, you can start by trying to find an infinitesimal change in velocity <m>d\vec{v}</m>.  By rewriting the definition of instantaneous acceleration as <m>d \vec{v} = \vec{a}(t) dt</m>, you can see that a way to get <m>d\vec{v}</m> is to <em>multiply</em> <m>\vec{a}(t)</m> and <m>dt</m>.</p>
	
		<p><term>Add:</term> Last, once you have the infinitesimal <m>d\vec{v}</m>, you need to <em>add</em> together every <m>d\vec{v}</m> over the full times of interest, which can be done with an integral: <me>\int_{v_i}^{v_f}d \vec{v} = \int_{t_i}^{t_f} \vec{a}(t) dt</me>  The left hand side of this equation can be easily evaluated to give <me>\Delta \vec{v} = \int_{t_i}^{t_f} \vec{a}(t) dt</me></p>
	

	<subsubsection>
<title>Activities</title>
			<activity>
				<title>Different Displacements</title>
				<p>
					
				</p>
				
			  <p>The following two equations are both reasonable to write down for a displacement vector: </p>
				<p><me>1: \Delta \vec{r} = \int_{t_i}^{t_f}\vec{v}(t)dt</me></p>
				<p><me>2: \Delta \vec{r}= \vec{v}\Delta t</me> </p>
				<p>What is the difference between them?  In what situations would you use the first equation?  In what situations would you use the second equation?</p>
			</activity>
			
		</subsubsection>

		
	
</section>

